title: For Sale:  Nylon 66
postcontent: For sale is a mint condition 1959 first year Remington Nylon 66.  This is one of the first mass produced polymer rifles.  It was given to me by my uncle who bought it brand new in 1959.  It is marked EF10 proving it was made in October of 1959 the first year the rifle was produced.  It still has the original tag that came around the trigger guard.  It also has the original instruction folder (manual) including the original New Remington Hispeed Kleanbore ammo that was displayed on the add in the manual that came with the rifle when purchased new.   My uncle only fired it a few times after he bought it.  I also fired a few rounds recently to confirm function.  It weighs only 4lbs has a 14 round capacity and tubular follower loaded through the stock.   This is everything that came with the rifle when it was new and was all kept in great condition.  Extremely rare to find an almost 60 year old rifle in mint condition that still has the manual that looks like it was made yesterday.  These are getting harder and harder to find in good condition.   Worn ones without original manual, trigger tag and ammo are selling for 350-400 and they are not first year of production with original papers.  This is a great collectors piece and will only go up in value if kept in its condition.  No oxidation or handling markers.  The front sight is still bright white and perfect shape.  Real safe queen wont find another one like it.  Looking for 475 or best offer.  I will be moving out of state and unfortunately am having to unload some of my collectors pieces.  Make me an offer worst i can say is no.

title: For Sale:  Grendel P10 380 acp
postcontent: For your consideration a have a relatively rare Grendel P10 in 380 acp. The Grendel was the predecessor to Keltec and owned by the same person. This unique 380 used an internal magazine that held an impressive 10 rounds in a very compact design. Loading could be done using a stripper clip or rounds could be loaded individually from the top through a locked back slide. No safety on this model, just a long double action pull. This was meant to market to police officers who were used to carrying revolvers and accustomed to loading rounds individually and a double action, hammer fired weapon. Unfortunately it came out at a time when police where making the switch over to semi autos. So this design was very short lived and very few ever made. This one comes in good condition and appears to function as it should. Bore and internals look to be in good shape. I have never fired or even loaded this gun. So, I cannot comment on how it shoots. I have no idea how many rounds have been fired through it before I acquired it. It does not come with anything but the pistol itself. No box or factory paperwork. It is what it is, just a cool, old, cheap, unique gun. Looking to get $150 cash. All laws apply. Foid, ISP check and wait period required. Pick up in St Charles or near by. Thanks and Merry Christmas!

title: For Sale:  Webley & Scott London M-1908 Police 32 Auto Pistol
postcontent: Please read the Item Characteristics for important listing details.Webley & Scott Model 1908 Self-Loading Pistol; ca.1916 Birmingham, England Production; .32 Auto(7.65mm)Classic and uncommon Webley & Scott M1908 Metroplitan Police Model...this pistol was manufactured ca.1916 in Birmingham and likely offered for retail in the UK. A standard example that is in good condition despite apparent holster wear, this 1908 features a 3.5" barrel, vulcanite grips, and external hammer. Adopted by the London Metropolitan Police in 1908, the M1908 is familiar to American collectors as the H&R Self-Loading Pistol, which was a licensed, hammerless copy of the British Webley. Although never officially adopted by the military, the M1908 was a popular officer's private purchase weapon, and saw favor with plainclothes cops as well as anyone in need of a discreet means of self-defense. In fine operating condition, this Webley M1908 may prove to be a fine shooter for the vintage pistol enthusiast and a worthy addition to any early 20th Century or British arms collection.ConditionGood, all-original condition, the finish has largely faded to a blue-tinged grey patina, with flashes or the originally dark, high-polish blue visible in the protected areas. There is no rust or deep pitting present on any of the pistol's exterior and only mild and occassional impact marks in places. Markings are well-struck, correct and include all Birmingham Proof House marks on the barrel, slide and frame, as well as the Webley address and brilliantly preserved Winged Bullet logo(pictured). Importantly, neither import nor export mark are present. Grips rate as good with wear to the checkering, a scrape on the left grip and a nick out of the point of contact with the safety lever. Mechanical function is excellent, and the bore rates as very good, having strong rifling with light frost running the length-it should clean nicely.December Shipping Blackout Dates: 12/11-12/15 & 12/25-12/29.Contact:For More Info Interested buyers should contactText Number: +1678-718-8067
